  <h2>The problem most people <em>do not see</em>.</h2>

  <p class="lead">
    You open ChatGPT. You ask it to write something. You copy-paste the output
    into another tab. You search for the file you generated yesterday. You can't
    find it. You try a different model. You hit a rate limit. You give up and
    go back to doing it manually.
  </p>

  <p>
    The problem is not the AI. The AI is fine. The problem is the <b>interface</b>.
  </p>
  <p>
    You're using AI like a vending machine — one ask, one answer, walk away.
    Meanwhile the people winning right now are running AI like an
    <b style="color: var(--gold);">operating system</b>. Memory across sessions.
    Agents that build things while they sleep. Generated assets that live in one
    searchable workspace. Voice in. Preview inline. Auto-saved to vault.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "The gap between people who figured out how to wire AI together and people
    still copy-pasting between tabs is now bigger than the gap between people
    with AI and people without it."
    <cite>— Julian Goldie</cite>
  </blockquote>

